  "prompt": "After it's ridiculous decision concerning the temple mount, are there still Israelis who take the UNESCO seriously?",
  "response": "The relationship between Israel and UNESCO has been complex and, at times, contentious, particularly regarding decisions related to cultural and religious sites like the Temple Mount in Jerusalem. In 2016, UNESCO passed resolutions that many Israelis and the Israeli government viewed as denying Jewish historical and religious connections to the Temple Mount, referring to it only by its Arabic name, Al-Haram Al-Sharif. This decision was widely criticized in Israel as politically motivated and historically inaccurate.\n\nAs a result, many Israelis, including government officials and the general public, have expressed skepticism about UNESCO's impartiality and credibility on matters related to Israel. In 2017, Israel announced that it would withdraw from UNESCO, citing a \"continuing bias against Israel\" as a key reason. The withdrawal took effect at the end of 2018.\n\nWhile some Israelis may still engage with UNESCO on specific issues or appreciate its broader cultural and educational mission, the organization's decisions regarding the Temple Mount and its perceived bias have significantly eroded its standing and credibility among many in Israel. The perception of UNESCO as a politicized body, particularly in the context of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, continues to influence Israeli attitudes toward the organization.",
